Here is a model for the church family - are we going to seek solidarity over self-interest?

“14 When Judah and his brothers came to Joseph’s house, he was still there. They fell before him to the ground. 15 Joseph said to them, “What deed is this that you have done? Do you not know that a man like me can indeed practice divination?” 16 And Judah said, “What shall we say to my lord? What shall we speak? Or how can we clear ourselves? God has found out the guilt of your servants; behold, we are my lord’s servants, both we and he also in whose hand the cup has been found.” 17 But he said, “Far be it from me that I should do so! Only the man in whose hand the cup was found shall be my servant. But as for you, go up in peace to your father.” 

Joseph said to them, “What deed is this that you have done? Do you not know that a man like me can indeed practice divination?”
He may have implied, “Why did you steal my cup? Don’t you know I need it for divining?” 
Or he may have implied, “Did you think you could get away with stealing my cup? You know I am a master of divination and would have found you out, one way or the other.” 
I prefer the second interpretation, for it underscores the utter helplessness of the brothers. They are foreigners in Egypt. They are thieves, or at least one of them is. They are at the mercy of a man who can track them anywhere with his divinatory power. Hamilton, V. P. (1995). The Book of Genesis, Chapters 18–50 (p. 565). Grand Rapids, MI: Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing Co.

 How does Judah respond to Joseph? What confession did Judah make to Joseph?

In this first speech Judah makes three points: 
he protests the brother’s innocence of the theft, 
How can we prove our innocence? The circumstantial evidence against them is so overwhelming, it is pointless to defend themselves.
confesses their dilemma as due to God’s judgment for previous guilt, 
God has uncovered your servants’ guilt. Judah was confessing that they were all guilty of sin, and God was now punishing them for it. 
God was  punishing them for the sin they had committed in the past, the terrible sin of having sold their brother into slavery. Judah did not mention this sin publicly.If so, they confess their crime against Joseph twice in his presence (42:21).

⇒Note the declaration of belief in God: that He holds us accountable.
Note the confession: they were all guilty of sin.
Note the repentance: they were now ready and willing to follow God’s will even if it meant being punished for their sins. Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). Genesis (Chapters 12–50) (Vol. II, p. 356). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.

and finally offers all of the brothers as slaves. In that way he undoes the rash oath to kill the guilty and avoids having to face their father.  Waltke, B. K., &amp; Fredricks, C. J. (2001). Genesis: a commentary (p. 561). Grand Rapids, MI: Zondervan.



 What punishment did Joseph insist upon?

Joseph just felt compelled to prove that the brothers were totally loyal to each other and to the family of God (v. 17). He declared that he could not enslave the innocent brothers, only the brother who had stolen the cup. Then he charged all the brothers to leave and go back home, all except Benjamin, the suspected thief. Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). Genesis (Chapters 12–50) (Vol. II, p. 356). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.


“18 Then Judah went up to him and said, “Oh, my lord, please let your servant speak a word in my lord’s ears, and let not your anger burn against your servant, for you are like Pharaoh himself. 19 My lord asked his servants, saying, ‘Have you a father, or a brother?’ 20 And we said to my lord, ‘We have a father, an old man, and a young brother, the child of his old age. His brother is dead, and he alone is left of his mother’s children, and his father loves him.’ 21 Then you said to your servants, ‘Bring him down to me, that I may set my eyes on him.’ 22 We said to my lord, ‘The boy cannot leave his father, for if he should leave his father, his father would die.’ 23 Then you said to your servants, ‘Unless your youngest brother comes down with you, you shall not see my face again.’ 

24 “When we went back to your servant my father, we told him the words of my lord. 25 And when our father said, ‘Go again, buy us a little food,’ 26 we said, ‘We cannot go down. If our youngest brother goes with us, then we will go down. For we cannot see the man’s face unless our youngest brother is with us.’ 27 Then your servant my father said to us, ‘You know that my wife bore me two sons. 28 One left me, and I said, “Surely he has been torn to pieces,” and I have never seen him since. 29 If you take this one also from me, and harm happens to him, you will bring down my gray hairs in evil to Sheol.’”

Summarize the story as Judah told it (vv 18-29).

Judah reminded Joseph of the demand he had made of them. Note the facts Judah stressed (vv. 18–23).
⇒	He reminded Joseph of his inquiry about their family, asking if they had a brother or father (v. 19).
⇒	He reminded Joseph of their father: that their father was old and had two other sons. One son was dead and the other son was the child of their father’s old age. And their father loved him dearly (v. 20).
⇒	He reminded Joseph of his demand to bring Benjamin to Egypt to prove that they were telling the truth (v. 21).
⇒	He reminded Joseph of their caution and reservation: taking Benjamin from their father might kill him (v. 22).
⇒	He reminded Joseph of his insistence: they had to bring Benjamin, or they would never be allowed to see the governor’s face again; they would never be allowed to get any more food (v. 23). Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). Genesis (Chapters 12–50) (Vol. II, p. 358). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.

Judah related how the brothers had told their father about the demand of the governor (vv. 24–29). Note that Joseph had no way to know about these facts. He was hearing for the very first time what had happened when his brothers had returned home to their father.
⇒	He related how the need for more food arose (v. 25).
⇒	He related how the sons reminded their father of the demand of the governor: the youngest brother had to go with them (v. 26).
⇒	He related their father’s response: his wife had borne him two sons and one had been torn to pieces (vv. 27–28).
⇒	He related how their father feared losing the second son: losing him would kill their father (v. 29).

30 “Now therefore, as soon as I come to your servant my father, and the boy is not with us, then, as his life is bound up in the boy’s life, 31 as soon as he sees that the boy is not with us, he will die, and your servants will bring down the gray hairs of your servant our father with sorrow to Sheol. 32 For your servant became a pledge of safety for the boy to my father, saying, ‘If I do not bring him back to you, then I shall bear the blame before my father all my life.’ 33 Now therefore, please let your servant remain instead of the boy as a servant to my lord, and let the boy go back with his brothers. 34 For how can I go back to my father if the boy is not with me? I fear to see the evil that would find my father.” 
 The Holy Bible: English Standard Version. (2016). (Ge 44:1–34). Wheaton: Standard Bible Society.

What problem did Judah fear (vv 30,31)?
That if Benjamin did not return to Canaan it would crush Jacob

Judah’s concern was his father. He did not want the heart of his father to be broken. Judah loved his father so much that he did not even want him to suffer pain. Note what he related to the governor:
⇒	Their father’s life was closely bound up with Benjamin (v. 30).
⇒	Their father would die if the boy were not with them when they returned home (v. 31a).
⇒	The sons—the servants of Joseph—would therefore be guilty of killing their father because they did not bring the boy home (v. 31b).

Why did Judah feel especially responsible for Benjamin?
He had made a pledge of safety to Jacob for Benjamin. He would bear all the blame if Benjamin should not return or suffer harm

What alternative did Judah propose, and what reason did he give (vv 33,34)? (Think: Note the similarities between Jesus’ sacrifice and what Judah proposed.)

Judah begged Joseph to take him as a slave instead of Benjamin

Judah then did an amazing thing. He offered to sacrifice himself for Benjamin (vv. 32–33). He asked Joseph to let him become the slave and to free Benjamin, letting him go home to his father (v. 32). He offered …
•	to become the substitute for Benjamin
•	to accept the punishment due Benjamin
•	to bear the guilt for Benjamin
•	to suffer in behalf of Benjamin
•	to give his life for the life of Benjamin
•	to switch places with Benjamin

Thought 2. Note how Judah became a magnificent picture of Christ in the above scene. Henry Morris states it well:
In this willingness to give his own life in place of his brother’s, for the sake of his father, Judah becomes a beautiful type of Christ, more fully and realistically than even Joseph himself, who is often taken by Bible expositors as a type of Christ. 

16 By this we know love, that he laid down his life for us, and we ought to lay down our lives for the brothers. The Holy Bible: English Standard Version. (2016). (1 Jn 3:16). Wheaton: Standard Bible Society.).

In fact, although Scripture does not say this in so many words, the problem as to why Judah, rather than Joseph, was selected to be the ancestor of the Messiah probably has its solution right here. Judah, in his willingness to sacrifice himself, the innocent for the guilty, had become the most Christlike of all his brothers.
This was it, the end of Judah’s speech. Joseph now knew that God had done a marvelous work in their lives. Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). Genesis (Chapters 12–50) (Vol. II, p. 359). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.


Special Assignment: Summarize how Judah’s statement showed the repentance of the brothers

It demonstrated that Judah and the brothers held no resentment against a son of Rachel
It demonstrated honesty and integrity
It demonstrated a willingness to self-sacrifice
It demonstrated unity

A spiritual metamorphosis for the better has certainly taken place in Judah. 
His speech to Joseph in ch. 44 represents a profound advancement over his speech about Joseph in 37:26ff. 
He who once callously engineered the selling of Joseph to strangers out of envy and anger is now willing to become Joseph’s slave so that the rest of his brothers, and especially Benjamin, may be freed and allowed to return to Canaan to rejoin their father.
