            <Text>50 Then Joseph fell on his father’s face and wept over him and kissed him. 2 And Joseph commanded his servants the physicians to embalm his father. So the physicians embalmed Israel. 3 Forty days were required for it, for that is how many are required for embalming. And the Egyptians wept for him seventy days. 

What did the physicians do with Jacob’s body? How long did it take? How long did the Egyptians mourn for him?

the physicians embalmed Israel
It took the embalmers forty days (a frequently used biblical number) to complete their work. Interestingly, the Egyptians mourned him for seventy days. More than likely this is not seventy more days after the completion of the embalming. Rather, the period of mourning extends beyond the embalming process by thirty days.

the Egyptians wept for him seventy days.
the Egyptians mourned. Not surprisingly, the whole nation mourns the father of their Hebrew savior (see 47:25)
seventy days. They were the days of mourning for an Egyptian king.


4 And when the days of weeping for him were past, Joseph spoke to the household of Pharaoh, saying, “If now I have found favor in your eyes, please speak in the ears of Pharaoh, saying, 5 ‘My father made me swear, saying, “I am about to die: in my tomb that I hewed out for myself in the land of Canaan, there shall you bury me.” Now therefore, let me please go up and bury my father. Then I will return.’ ” 6 And Pharaoh answered, “Go up, and bury your father, as he made you swear.” 7 So Joseph went up to bury his father. With him went up all the servants of Pharaoh, the elders of his household, and all the elders of the land of Egypt, 8 as well as all the household of Joseph, his brothers, and his father’s household. Only their children, their flocks, and their herds were left in the land of Goshen. 9 And there went up with him both chariots and horsemen. It was a very great company. 

What request did Joseph then make? Why?

He asked Pharaoh to let him bury Jacob in Canaan 
Because this was Jacob's request 

Who went with Joseph? Who/what did not go? (Think: What is indicated by the fact all these people went?)

With him went up all the servants of Pharaoh, the elders of his household, and all the elders of the land of Egypt, as well as all the household of Joseph, his brothers, and his father’s household
Three different groups participate in Jacob’s funeral procession: (1) high-ranking members of Pharaoh’s bureaucracy, v. 7; (2) male survivors of Jacob’s family, v. 8 (what of Leah and his concubines—are they still living?); (3) a military escort, v. 9.
Only their children, their flocks, and their herds were left in the land of Goshen.




10 When they came to the threshing floor of Atad, which is beyond the Jordan, they lamented there with a very great and grievous lamentation, and he made a mourning for his father seven days. 11 When the inhabitants of the land, the Canaanites, saw the mourning on the threshing floor of Atad, they said, “This is a grievous mourning by the Egyptians.” Therefore the place was named Abel-mizraim; it is beyond the Jordan. 12 Thus his sons did for him as he had commanded them, 13 for his sons carried him to the land of Canaan and buried him in the cave of the field at Machpelah, to the east of Mamre, which Abraham bought with the field from Ephron the Hittite to possess as a burying place. 14 After he had buried his father, Joseph returned to Egypt with his brothers and all who had gone up with him to bury his father. 

 Where did they stop and why (v10)? How did this affect the Canaanites?

They stopped at the threshing floor of Atad, which is beyond the Jordan to lament and mourn for seven days 
Atad. The sixth century a.d. Madeba mosaic map locates an Alon Atad (terebinth of Atad) near Beth Agla (Beth Hogla—modern Deir Hajlah) between Jericho and the Dead Sea. Is Jacob in his death showing his descendants the road to the Promised Land?
Seven days was the normal period for mourning (see 1 Sam. 31:13 par. 1 Chr. 10:12; 2 Sam. 11:27; Job 2:13; Jdt. 16:24; Sir. 10:12)
The Canaanites said, “This is a grievous mourning by the Egyptians.”

What name was given to this place, and what does the name mean?

The place was named Abel-mizraim. It means “mourning of Egypt”
Upon seeing this ritual, the residents state: How grievously the Egyptians are mourning! Moved by this scene, they rename the vicinity Abelmizraim, thus providing another instance of etiological narrative in Genesis.

What did Jacob’s sons do with Jacob’s body? What promise did this fulfill?

They buried him in the cave of the field at Machpelah, to the east of Mamre, which Abraham bought with the field from Ephron the Hittite to possess as a burying place
The sons carry out their father’s last wish. They bury him in the cave of Machpelah where Jacob’s father, and grandfather, and one of his wives (Leah) are buried. 
Thus Jacob leaves one part of his family and joins another part of his family. Perhaps the recall of Abraham’s purchase of this real estate from Ephron the Hittite (see Gen. 23) is prompted by the use of the word ʾaḥuzzá (“burial site”)

God’s Good Purposes
15 When Joseph’s brothers saw that their father was dead, they said, “It may be that Joseph will hate us and pay us back for all the evil that we did to him.” 16 So they sent a message to Joseph, saying, “Your father gave this command before he died: 17 ‘Say to Joseph, “Please forgive the transgression of your brothers and their sin, because they did evil to you.” ’ And now, please forgive the transgression of the servants of the God of your father.” Joseph wept when they spoke to him. 18 His brothers also came and fell down before him and said, “Behold, we are your servants.” 19 But Joseph said to them, “Do not fear, for am I in the place of God? 20 As for you, you meant evil against me, but God meant it for good, to bring it about that many people should be kept alive, as they are today. 21 So do not fear; I will provide for you and your little ones.” Thus he comforted them and spoke kindly to them. 

What concern did Joseph’s brothers then have, and what did they do about it?

They were afraid that Joseph would exact revenge 
They sent a message to Joseph, saying, “Your father gave this command before he died: ‘Say to Joseph, “Please forgive the transgression of your brothers and their sin, because they did evil to you.” ’ And now, please forgive the transgression of the servants of the God of your father.”
His brothers also came and fell down before him and said, “Behold, we are your servants.”

How did Joseph respond to his brothers? How did he say he would treat them? (Think: Review what this teaches about forgiveness and God’s providence.)

But note Joseph’s response: he would not accept their offer to be his servants. He would keep his forgiving spirit. 
He had forgiven his brothers years before, over seventeen years earlier. 
He had never gone back on his promise of forgiveness (vv. 19–21). Joseph had truly forgiven. This meant that he had asked God to give him God’s very own spirit of forgiveness. 
What is God’s spirit of forgiveness?
⇒ Once forgiven, always forgiven.
There is no other forgiveness, not true forgiveness. True forgiveness does just that: it forgives once and for all. The old sin or wrong is never brought up again. It cannot be, not if it has been truly forgiven.

Of course, this is difficult to accept, especially if we are the guilty party upon whom vengeance can fall. 
This was the problem the brothers were having. They were not sure that Joseph had truly forgiven them. 
But Joseph wanted to assure them: he had forgiven them, and he had kept on forgiving them. He could do nothing less, for he was following God to the end. 
And God demands that we forgive, forgive once and for all. Note how Joseph sought to convince his brothers of his forgiveness.

Why was Joseph able to forgive?

God’s place to judge, not his. He was, therefore, leaving the judgment up to God.
God overrules man’s evil and uses it for good

20 But as for you, ye thought evil against me; but God meant it unto good, to bring to pass, as it is this day, to save much people alive.

Joseph declared that God had overruled their evil and worked it out for good (v. 20). This was the same declaration Joseph had made to his brothers seventeen years earlier. 
He had seen God’s hand taking all the terrible circumstances of his life and working them out for good. God had used all the terrible trials to strengthen him and to teach him to endure and to work hard. 
Thus God was able to exalt Joseph to be the ruler of Egypt so that he could save the world of his day from utter catastrophe. 
God had used Joseph to save the world, but especially His people, Israel, the believers of the earth; to save them from total economic collapse and starvation due to the seven-year famine that had struck the known world of that day.

One must repay evil with good: He promised to take care of his brothers &amp; assured them

Joseph declared that he must repay evil with good (v. 21). He must do exactly what Scripture says we must do:
“Be not overcome of evil, but overcome evil with good” (Ro. 12:21).
Joseph encouraged his brothers not to fear: he was going to provide for them and their families. 
Note how he did all he could to reassure his brothers. He spoke only kind and comforting words to them (v. 21﻿b).

Thought 1. What a dynamic example of forgiving others! If Joseph could forgive his brothers, we can forgive any person for anything. No matter how terrible the wrong or evil done against us, we can forgive the person. In fact, we must. God demands that we forgive them.


The Death of Joseph
22 So Joseph remained in Egypt, he and his father’s house. Joseph lived 110 years. 23 And Joseph saw Ephraim’s children of the third generation. The children also of Machir the son of Manasseh were counted as Joseph’s own. 24 And Joseph said to his brothers, “I am about to die, but God will visit you and bring you up out of this land to the land that he swore to Abraham, to Isaac, and to Jacob.” 25 Then Joseph made the sons of Israel swear, saying, “God will surely visit you, and you shall carry up my bones from here.” 26 So Joseph died, being 110 years old. They embalmed him, and he was put in a coffin in Egypt.  The Holy Bible: English Standard Version. (2016). (Ge 50). Wheaton: Standard Bible Society.

What are we told about the rest of Joseph’s life (vv 22,23)?

Joseph remained in Egypt, he and his father’s house. 
Joseph lived 110 years. 
Joseph saw Ephraim’s children of the third generation.

23 Makir. This is the most important clan of Manasseh, even identified with the whole tribe. The name, which means “one who is sold,” is probably a word play with the life of Joseph.

24. to his brothers. The word may mean “relatives.” If it means “brothers” in the strict sense, then some or all of his older brothers outlive him.

take you up out of this land. This is a technical phrase for the Exodus from Egypt (see Gen. 15:13–14). Joseph speaks as a prophet, perhaps informed by God’s promise to Abraham.

Joseph hung on to the great promises of God even as he faced death. we hang on to the great promises of God, never letting go. 

Joseph declared the deliverance of Israel from Egypt; that they would inherit the promised land

the land he swore/promised. The theme of the patriarchs is on Joseph’s lips at death. The land is a divine gift to the elect family.

Joseph declared that God was going to deliver Israel out of Egypt and take them back to the promised land (v. 24﻿b). 
Imagine, Joseph had been living out of the promised land for over 90 years. Yet, here he was declaring his faith in the great promises of God. 
This possibly could be considered a prophecy by Joseph, but more likely it is just a strong declaration of his faith.

Now, note what Joseph did. It was very significant, so significant that Joseph demanded an oath from his brothers. 
He made them swear that they would carry his bones back to the promised land when they returned (v. 25). 
This was one of the greatest declarations of faith in the promises of God ever made by a person. Remember: it was to be four hundred years before Joseph’s bones could be buried in Canaan

By faith Joseph, when he died, made mention of the departing of the children of Israel; and gave commandment concerning his bones” (He. 11:22).

The request of Joseph was to be fulfilled. Israel took his bones with them when they returned to the promised land. Moses himself took the bones of Joseph out of Egypt (Ex. 13:19), and some years later his bones were buried at Shechem, buried in a tract of land that Jacob had bought (Jos. 24:32).</Text>
